<section id="sect-00003">
<title>Glycoside Formation</title>
<para id="para-00006">We saw in <link document="m00221"/> that treatment of a hemiacetal with an alcohol and an acid catalyst yields an acetal.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down-30" id="fig-00003">
<media alt="An illustration shows a reversible chemical reaction. A hemiacetal reacts with an alcohol in the presence of hydrochloric acid to form an acetal and water highlighted in pink. The hemiacetal shows a carbon bonded to a hydroxyl group highlighted in pink and to O-R highlighted in blue; the carbon shows a free wedge bond and dash bond. The alcohol shows a hydroxyl group bonded to R where the R and oxygen are highlighted in blue and the hydrogen in pink. The acetal shows a carbon bonded to two O-R groups which are highlighted in blue; the carbon shows a free wedge bond and dash bond.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_25_06_004.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00007">In the same way, treatment of a monosaccharide hemiacetal with an alcohol and an acid catalyst yields an acetal called a <term id="term-00001">glycoside</term>, in which the anomeric –OH has been replaced by an –OR group. For example, reaction of <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-<emphasis effect="smallcaps">D</emphasis>-glucopyranose with methanol gives a mixture of <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis> and <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis> methyl <emphasis effect="smallcaps">D</emphasis>-glucopyranosides. (Note that a <emphasis effect="italics">gly</emphasis>coside is the functional group name for any sugar, whereas a <emphasis effect="italics">glu</emphasis>coside is formed specifically from glucose.)</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00004">
<media alt="An illustration shows a reversible chemical reaction. Beta-D-glucopyranose a cyclic hemiacetal reacts with blue methanol and hydrochloric acid to form 66 percent of Methyl-alpha-D-glucopyranoside and 33 percent of Methyl beta-D-glucopyranoside. The chair conformation of beta-D-glucopyranose shows a six-carbon ring with the ring oxygen highlighted in green. The equatorial hydroxyl groups are bonded to C2 C3 and C4. The hydroxyl group on C1 is highlighted in pink; a hydroxymethyl group is bonded to C5. Methyl-alpha-D-glucopyranoside and Methyl beta-D-glucopyranoside show a methoxy group highlighted in blue replacing the hydrogen of the hydroxyl group on C1; it points axial down in Methyl-alpha-D-glucopyranoside and equatorial up in the Methyl-beta-D-glucopyranoside.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_25_06_005.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00008">Glycosides are named by first citing the alkyl group and then replacing the -<emphasis effect="italics">ose</emphasis> ending of the sugar with -<emphasis effect="italics">oside.</emphasis> Like all acetals, glycosides are stable in neutral water. They aren’t in equilibrium with an open-chain form, and they don’t show mutarotation. They can, however, be hydrolyzed to give back the free monosaccharide plus alcohol on treatment with aqueous acid (<link document="m00221"/>).</para>
<para id="para-00009">Glycosides are abundant in nature, and many biologically important molecules contain glycosidic linkages. For example, digitoxin, the active component of the digitalis preparations used for treatment of heart disease, is a glycoside consisting of a steroid alcohol linked to a trisaccharide. Note also that the three sugars are linked to one another by glycoside bonds.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00005">
<media alt="An illustration shows the structure of digitoxin a glycoside where a trisaccharide is bonded to the third carbon of a steroid. The ring oxygen in each sugar is highlighted in green and the oxygen atoms involved in the glycosidic linkages are highlighted in pink. In the trisaccharide each unit shows a pyranose in the chair conformation with a hydroxyl group at C4 and a methyl group at C5. A monosaccharide is bonded to the next by a 1→4 glycosidic bond. The steroid shows three cyclohexane rings fused with one five-member cyclopentane ring. The first cyclohexane is wedge bonded to pink oxygen and dash bonded to hydrogen. The first two rings share a wedge bonded methyl group and wedge bonded hydrogen. The second and third rings share a dash bonded hydrogen and wedge bonded hydrogen; the third ring and the cyclopentane ring share a wedge bonded methyl group and wedge bonded hydroxyl group. The cyclopentane is dash bonded to a hydrogen and wedge bonded to a cyclopentanone that shows an oxygen.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_25_06_006.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00010">The laboratory synthesis of glycosides can be difficult because of the numerous –OH groups on the sugar molecule. One method that is particularly suitable for preparing glucose <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-glycosides involves treatment of glucose pentaacetate with HBr, followed by addition of the appropriate alcohol in the presence of silver oxide. Called the <term id="term-00002">Koenigs–Knorr reaction</term>, the sequence involves formation of a pyranosyl bromide, followed by nucleophilic substitution. For example, methylarbutin, a glycoside found in pears, has been prepared by reaction of tetraacetyl-<emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>-<emphasis effect="smallcaps">D</emphasis>-glucopyranosyl bromide with <emphasis effect="italics">p</emphasis>-methoxyphenol.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered" id="fig-00006">
<media alt="An illustration shows the Koenigs–Knorr reaction. Pentaacetyl-beta-D-glucopyranose reacts with hydrogen bromide highlighted in pink to form Tetraacetyl-alpha-D-glucopyranosyl bromide which reacts with ArOH highlighted in blue and silver oxide then with aqueous sodium hydroxide to form Methylarbutin. Pentaacetyl-beta-D-glucopyranose shows four acetyl groups and a methyl acetate group bonded to glucopyranose which is represented in the chair conformation. Tetraacetyl-alpha-D-pyranosyl bromide shows three acetyl groups bonded to C2 C3 and C4. C5 is bonded to a methyl acetate group; a bromine atom highlighted in pink is bonded to C1. Methylarbutin is similar to the intermediate but C2 C3 and C4 are bonded to a hydroxyl group each. C1 is bonded to a blue oxygen bonded to benzene bonded to methoxide group.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_25_06_007.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00011">Although the Koenigs–Knorr reaction appears to involve a simple backside S<sub>N</sub>2 displacement of bromide ion by alkoxide ion, the situation is actually more complex. Both <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis> and <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis> anomers of tetraacetyl-<emphasis effect="smallcaps">D</emphasis>-glucopyranosyl bromide give the same <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-glycoside product, implying that they react by a common pathway.</para>
<para id="para-00012">This result can be understood by assuming that tetraacetyl-<emphasis effect="smallcaps">D</emphasis>-glucopyranosyl bromide (either <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis> or <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis> anomer) undergoes a spontaneous S<sub>N</sub>1-like loss of Br<sup>–</sup>, followed by internal reaction with the ester group at C2 to form an oxonium ion. Since the acetate at C2 is on the bottom of the glucose ring, the C–O bond also forms from the bottom. Backside S<sub>N</sub>2 displacement of the oxonium ion then occurs with the usual inversion of configuration, yielding a <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-glycoside and regenerating the acetate at C2 (<link target-id="fig-00007"/>).</para>
<figure class="scaled-down" id="fig-00007">
<media alt="An illustration shows the mechanism of the Koenigs–Knorr reaction. Either anomer of Tetraacetyl-D-glucopyranosyl bromide forms a beta-glycoside with two intermediates. Tetraacetyl-D-pyranosyl bromide shows four acetyl groups bonded to C2 C3 C4 and C6 of alpha-D-glucopyranose; the ring oxygen and the bromine atom bonded to C1 are highlighted in pink. In the first step an arrow points from the two lone electrons on the ring oxygen to the bond linking it to the first carbon. Another arrow points from the bond linking bromine to C1 to bromine. The next two steps are enclosed in square brackets. An arrow points from the double bond between the ring oxygen and C1 to the ring oxygen which has two electrons and a positive charge. Another arrow points from one of two pairs of electrons on the oxygen of the acetyl group highlighted in green bonded via an ester oxygen to C2 to C1. Next a bond forms between the oxygen which now has one pair of electrons and a positive charge to C1; an arrow points from this bond to the positively charged oxygen of the acetyl group. The double bond is replaced by a single bond and the ring oxygen is now neutral. An arrow also points from a negatively charged oxygen with three pairs of electrons bonded to R to C1. In the final step the intermediate product reacts with alcohol represented by R-OH highlighted in blue and silver oxide to form a beta-glycoside. The beta-glycoside shows O-R highlighted in blue bonded to C1 and acetyl groups bonded to C2 C3 C4 and C6.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_25_06_008.jpg"/>
</media>
<caption><emphasis effect="bold">Mechanism of the Koenigs–Knorr reaction, showing the neighboring-group effect of a nearby acetate.</emphasis></caption>
</figure>
<para id="para-00013">The participation shown by the nearby acetate group in the Koenigs–Knorr reaction is referred to as a <emphasis effect="italics">neighboring-group effect</emphasis> and is a common occurrence in organic chemistry. Neighboring-group effects are usually noticeable only because they affect the rate or stereochemistry of a reaction; the nearby group itself does not undergo any evident change during the reaction.</para>
</section>
<section id="sect-00004">
<title>Biological Ester Formation: Phosphorylation</title>
<para id="para-00014">In living organisms, carbohydrates occur not only in the free form but also linked through their anomeric center to other molecules such as lipids (glycolipids) or proteins (glycoproteins). Collectively called <emphasis effect="italics">glycoconjugates,</emphasis> these sugar-linked molecules are components of cell walls that are crucial to the mechanism by which different cell types recognize one another.</para>
<para id="para-00015">Glycoconjugate formation occurs by reaction of the lipid or protein with a glycosyl nucleoside diphosphate. This diphosphate is itself formed by initial reaction of a monosaccharide with adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to give a glycosyl monophosphate, followed by reaction with uridine triphosphate (UTP), to give a glycosyl uridine diphosphate. (We’ll see the structures of nucleoside phosphates in <emphasis effect="bold">Section 28.1</emphasis>.) The purpose of the phosphorylation is to activate the anomeric –OH group of the sugar and make it a better leaving group in a nucleophilic substitution reaction by a protein or lipid (<link target-id="fig-00008"/>).</para>
<figure class="scaled-down" id="fig-00008">
<media alt="An illustration shows the formation of a glycoprotein. D-Glucose is converted to D-Glucosyl phosphate; ATP highlighted in green is converted to ADP highlighted in blue. The chair conformation of glucose shows a cyclohexane with a hydroxyl group at C2 C3 and C4; a hydroxymethyl group is bonded to C5. The hydroxyl group bonded to C1 is highlighted in pink. D-Glucosyl phosphate shows a phosphate group highlighted in green replacing the hydrogen of the hydroxyl group at C1. A phosphate group shows a central phosphorus atom double bonded to an oxygen and single bonded to two oxygen anions. D-Glucosyl phosphate reacts with Uridine 5 prime-triphosphate (UTP) to form D-Glucosyluridine 5 prime-diphosphate (UDP-Glucose) releasing inorganic pyrophosphate (PPi). UTP shows a pyrimidine base uracil which has a keto group at the fourth and sixth carbon positions; the nitrogen at position 1 of the base is bonded to the C1 of the sugar ribose which shows a phosphate group at C5. Ribose shows a five-carbon ring with a hydrogen atom at positions 1 and 4 a hydroxyl group and a hydrogen atom at positions 2 and 3; C4 is bonded to C5 that is bonded to two hydrogen atoms and an oxygen that is bonded to a chain of three phosphate groups; the alpha phosphate is highlighted in green. D-Glucosyluridine 5 prime-diphosphate is similar to D-Glucosyl phosphate but the phosphate group is bonded to another phosphate group bonded to a methylene group that is bonded to ribose which is bonded to uracil. D-Glucosyluridine 5 prime-diphosphate reacts with a hydroxyl group highlighted in blue attached to a protein to form a glycoprotein releasing UDP which is highlighted in green. The glycoprotein shows the protein attached via the oxygen to C1 of D-glucose.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_25_06_009.jpg"/>
</media>
<caption><emphasis effect="bold">Glycoprotein formation occurs by initial phosphorylation of the starting carbohydrate with ATP to a glycosyl monophosphate, followed by reaction with UTP to form a glycosyl uridine 5′-diphosphate.</emphasis> Nucleophilic substitution by an –OH (or –NH<sub>2</sub>) group on a protein then gives the glycoprotein.</caption>
</figure>
</section>
<section id="sect-00005">
<title>Reduction of Monosaccharides</title>
<para id="para-00016">Treatment of an aldose or ketose with NaBH<sub>4</sub> reduces it to a polyalcohol called an <term id="term-00003">alditol</term>. The reduction occurs by reaction of the open-chain form present in the aldehyde/ketone <m:math><m:mo>⇄</m:mo></m:math> hemiacetal equilibrium. Although only a small amount of the open-chain form is present at any given time, that small amount is reduced, more is produced by opening of the pyranose form, that additional amount is reduced, and so on, until the entire sample has undergone reaction.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00009">
<media alt="An illustration shows the structure of beta-D-glucopyranose and a reversible chemical reaction of D-glucose to D-glucitol. D-Glucose reacts with sodium borohydride highlighted in blue and water to form D-Glucitol (D-Sorbitol) an alditol. The chair conformation of D-Glucose shows a six-carbon ring with the ring oxygen highlighted in green. Hydroxyl groups are bonded to C2 C3 and C4. The hydroxyl group on C1 highlighted in pink is on the same face as the hydroxymethyl group (C6) bonded to C5. The Fischer projection of D-Glucose shows C1 bonded to a hydrogen and double bonded to an oxygen that is highlighted in pink hydroxyl groups on C2 C4 and C5 that lie on the right of the carbon and the hydrogen atoms bonded to these carbons lie on the left. At C3 the hydrogen lies on the left and the hydroxyl on the right. The hydroxyl group bonded to C5 is highlighted in green. C6 is bonded to hydrogen atoms and a hydroxymethyl group. The structure of D-Glucitol is like that of D-Glucose except that the first carbon is bonded to two hydrogen atoms and a hydroxyl group.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_25_06_010.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00017"><emphasis effect="smallcaps">D</emphasis>-Glucitol, the alditol produced by reduction of <emphasis effect="smallcaps">D</emphasis>-glucose, is itself a naturally occurring substance found in many fruits and berries. It is used under the name <emphasis effect="smallcaps">D</emphasis>-sorbitol as a sweetener and sugar substitute in many foods.</para>
</section>
