<section id="sect-00007">
<title>Oxidation of Monosaccharides</title>
<para id="para-00020">Like other aldehydes, aldoses are easily oxidized to yield the corresponding carboxylic acids, called <term id="term-00004">aldonic acids</term>. A buffered solution of aqueous Br<sub>2</sub> is often used for this purpose.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00010">
<media alt="An illustration shows a reversible chemical reaction. D-Glucose reacts with bromine and water both highlighted in pink to form D-Gluconic acid an aldonic acid at pH 6. The chair conformation of D-Glucose shows a six-carbon ring with the ring oxygen highlighted in green. Hydroxyl groups are bonded to C2 C3 and C4. The hydroxyl group on C1 highlighted in pink is on the same face as the hydroxymethyl group (C6) bonded to C5. The Fischer projection of D-Glucose shows C1 bonded to a hydrogen and double bonded to an oxygen that is highlighted in pink hydroxyl groups on C2 C4 and C5 that lie on the right of the carbon and the hydrogen atoms bonded to these carbons lie on the left. At C3 the hydrogen lies on the left and the hydroxyl on the right. The hydroxyl group bonded to C5 is highlighted in green. C6 is bonded to hydrogen atoms and a hydroxymethyl group. The structure of D-Gluconic acid is like that of D-Glucose except that the hydrogen on the first carbon is converted to a hydroxyl group highlighted in pink.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_25_06_011.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00021">Historically, the oxidation of an aldose with either Ag<sup>+</sup> in aqueous ammonia (called <emphasis effect="italics">Tollens’ reagent</emphasis>) or Cu<sup>2+</sup> with aqueous sodium citrate (<emphasis effect="italics">Benedict’s reagent</emphasis>) formed the basis of simple tests for what are called <term id="term-00005">reducing sugars</term>. (<emphasis effect="italics">Reducing</emphasis> because the aldose reduces the metal oxidizing agent.) Some simple diabetes self-test kits sold in drugstores still use Benedict’s reagent to detect glucose in urine, though more modern methods have largely replaced it.</para>
<para id="para-00022">All aldoses are reducing sugars because they contain an aldehyde group, but some ketoses are reducing sugars as well. Fructose reduces Tollens’ reagent, for example, even though it contains no aldehyde group. Reduction occurs because fructose is readily isomerized to a mixture of aldoses (glucose and mannose) in basic solution by a series of keto–enol tautomeric shifts (<link target-id="fig-00011"/>). Glycosides, however, are nonreducing because the acetal group is not hydrolyzed to an aldehyde under basic conditions.</para>
<figure class="scaled-down" id="fig-00011">
<media alt="An illustration shows reversible chemical reactions. D-Fructose reacts with aqueous sodium hydroxide to first form an enediol and then form a mixture of D-Glucose and D-Mannose. In D-Fructose the first carbon is bonded to two hydrogen atoms a hydroxyl group that is highlighted in green and the second carbon which is part of the ketone functional group. The carbonyl oxygen is highlighted in pink. The hydroxyl group on C4 and C5 lie on the right while that on C3 lies on the left. The hydrogen on C4 and C5 lie on the left while that on C3 lies on the right. C6 is bonded to two hydrogen atoms and a hydroxyl group on the right. In the enediol the first carbon is now bonded to a hydroxyl group highlighted in green a hydrogen and double-bonded to the second carbon which is bonded to a hydroxyl group highlighted in pink. The Fischer projection of D-Glucose shows C1 bonded to a hydrogen and double bonded to an oxygen that is highlighted in green hydroxyl groups on C2 C4 and C5 that lie on the right of the carbon and the hydrogen atoms bonded to these carbons lie on the left. At C3 the hydrogen lies on the left and the hydroxyl on the right. The hydroxyl group bonded to C5 is highlighted in green. C6 is bonded to hydrogen atoms and a hydroxymethyl group. The Fischer projection of D-Mannose shows the first carbon bonded to a hydrogen and double-bonded to an oxygen highlighted in green. Carbons 2 and 3 are bonded to a hydrogen on the right and a hydroxyl on the left. Carbons 4 and 5 are bonded to a hydroxyl on the right and a hydrogen on the left. The sixth carbon is bonded to two hydrogen atoms and a hydroxyl group.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_25_06_012.jpg"/>
</media>
<caption><emphasis effect="bold">Fructose, a ketose, is a reducing sugar because it undergoes two base-catalyzed keto–enol tautomerizations that result in conversion to a mixture of aldoses.</emphasis></caption>
</figure>
<para id="para-00023">If warm, dilute HNO<sub>3</sub> (nitric acid) is used as the oxidizing agent, an aldose is oxidized to a dicarboxylic acid called an <term id="term-00006">aldaric acid</term>. Both the aldehyde carbonyl and the terminal –CH<sub>2</sub>OH group are oxidized in this reaction.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00012">
<media alt="An illustration shows the structure of D-glucose and its reversible chemical reaction. D-Glucose reacts with warm dilute nitric acid to form D-Glucaric acid an aldaric acid. The chair conformation of D-Glucose shows a six-carbon ring. Hydroxyl groups are bonded to C2 C3 C4 and C5. The hydroxyl group on C1 highlighted in pink is on the same face as the hydroxymethyl group (C6); the hydroxyl group bonded to C6 is highlighted in pink. The Fischer projection of D-Glucose shows C1 bonded to a hydrogen and double bonded to an oxygen that is highlighted in pink hydroxyl groups on C2 C4 and C5 that lie on the right of the carbon and the hydrogen atoms bonded to these carbons lie on the left; the hydroxyl group bonded to C6 is highlighted in pink. At C3 the hydrogen lies on the left and the hydroxyl on the right. C6 is bonded to hydrogen atoms and a hydroxymethyl group. The structure of D-Glucaric acid is like that of D-Glucose except that the first carbon is bonded to a hydroxyl group and double-bonded to an oxygen both highlighted in pink and the sixth carbon is also bonded to a hydroxyl group and double-bonded to an oxygen both highlighted in pink.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_25_06_013.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00024">Finally, if only the –CH<sub>2</sub>OH end of the aldose is oxidized without affecting the –CHO group, the product is a monocarboxylic acid called a <term id="term-00007">uronic acid</term>. The reaction can only be done enzymatically; no chemical reagent is known that can accomplish this selective oxidation in the laboratory.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00013">
<media alt="An illustration shows a chemical reaction. D-Glucose is oxidized by an enzyme to form D-Glucuronic acid a uronic acid. The chair conformation of D-Glucose shows a six-carbon ring. Hydroxyl groups are bonded to C2 C3 and C4. The hydroxyl group on C1 highlighted in pink is on the same face as the hydroxymethyl group (C6) bonded to C5; the hydroxymethyl group is highlighted in pink. D-Glucuronic acid represented both in chair conformation and Fischer projection shows a similar structure to that of D-Glucose except that the sixth carbon is bonded to a hydroxyl group and double-bonded to an oxygen all highlighted in pink.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_25_06_014.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
